      • initialUpdate

        public void initialUpdate()
        Description copied from class: TileEntityTickableSafe
        Like TileEntity.onLoad(), except that it is safe (see TileEntityTickableSafe.safeUpdate()) and happens after the world has loaded. onLoad() occurs during the world loading process, so you cannot access any blockstate values or anything of that sort. This is designed to be used for initialization stuff.

        This is called before TileEntityTickableSafe.safeUpdate() is called.

        You must either call the supermethod or TileEntityTickableSafe.setInitialized(boolean) in your implementation, or at some point during update or safeUpdate, otherwise this method will repeatedly get called.

        This is not necessarily the first update. Rather, it is the first update after the TE has been uninitialized. It just happens to also begin uninitialized. It truly is called whenever an update occurs and the TE is not initialized (see TileEntityTickableSafe.isInitialized()).

        For example, you might have a device that sets some value in the TE based on the block's facing value. The facing value probably won't change, so it doesn't make sense to retrieve that value every update. Using this, you would store the value once, and then simply use it in TileEntityTickableSafe.safeUpdate() when you need. However, if you had some custom behavior utilizing a PipeWrench that would rotate the block, you would need to reset that value in the TE. You can do that by having a proxy method in the TE that calls TileEntityTickableSafe.setInitialized(boolean) (since that method is protected for security reasons; more on that later) so that the next update resets the value in the TE.

        Here is a code sample for the scenario previously described: 

         
     // SomeTileEntity.java
     class SomeTileEntity extends TileEntityTickableSafe {
         private EnumFacing facing;

          @Override
         public void initialUpdate() {
             super.initialUpdate();
             facing = worldObj.getBlockState(pos).getValue(SomeBlock.FACING);
         }

          @Override
         public void safeUpdate() {
             // Destroys the block in the direction it is facing, for example.
             worldObj.destroyBlock(pos.offset(facing), true);
         }

         void uninitialize() {
             setInitialized(false);
         }
     }

     // SomeBlock.java, in same package
     class SomeBlock extends Block implements Wrenchable {
         static final PropertyDirection FACING = BlockDirectional.FACING;

         // IBlockState implementations

          @Override
         public boolean onWrench(ItemStack stack, EntityPlayer player, World world, BlockPos pos, EnumHand hand, EnumFacing facing, IBlockState state, float hitX, float hitY, float hitZ) {
             // Rotate the block
             world.setBlockState(pos, state.withProperty(FACING, state.getValue(FACING).rotateY()));
             TileEntity te = world.getTileEntity(pos);
             if (te instanceof SomeTileEntity) {
                 // Uninitialize the tile entity since our facing value has changed.
                 ((SomeTileEntity) te).uninitialize();
             }
         }
     }

      • explode

        public void explode()
        Description copied from interface: SteamTransporter
        Explodes the transporter and removes it from the steamnet. This should handle any reductions in steamnet steam or pressure. You do not have to actually make an explosion if you don't want to. This is called if SteamTransporter.shouldExplode() has been called. It must be called during the block/tile entity's update/tick.
